Project Summary: Near-Earth Object (NEO) Explorer
This is a Udacity "Advanced Python Techniques" course project — a command-line tool to search and explore asteroid/comet close approaches to Earth using NASA/JPL data.

What It Does
Users can:

Inspect individual NEOs by designation (e.g., 433) or name (e.g., Halley)
Query close approach events with filters (date range, distance, velocity, diameter, hazard status)
Export results to CSV or JSON files
Run interactively in a REPL shell for repeated queries
How to Run It
No dependencies to install — pure Python standard library only.


# Inspect a NEO
python3 main.py inspect --pdes 433
python3 main.py inspect --name Halley --verbose

# Query with filters
python3 main.py query --start-date 2020-01-01 --end-date 2020-12-31 --max-distance 0.025
python3 main.py query --min-diameter 0.5 --hazardous --limit 5 --outfile results.csv

# Interactive shell
python3 main.py interactive

# Run tests
python3 -m unittest --verbose
Default data files are data/neos.csv (75-column NEO catalog) and data/cad.json (~406k close approach events).

APIs, Libraries, and Data Sources
Details
Data source	NASA JPL CNEOS — SBDB API & CAD API (data pre-downloaded as local files)
Libraries	csv, json, datetime, argparse, cmd, operator, pathlib — stdlib only
No third-party packages	Pure Python 3.6+
