Here's a summary of every change made and what each relies on:

models.py
NearEarthObject.__init__: reads designation, name, diameter, hazardous from **info. name is set to None if the string is empty (or None). diameter uses float() if present, else float('nan'). hazardous compares to 'Y' (the CSV value).
NearEarthObject.fullname: simple f-string — "433 (Eros)" or just "433".
NearEarthObject.__str__: uses fullname and hazardous.
CloseApproach.__init__: same pattern; time is parsed by cd_to_datetime (already imported from helpers.py) which calls datetime.strptime with the NASA "%Y-%b-%d %H:%M" format.
CloseApproach.time_str: delegates to datetime_to_str (also already imported from helpers.py).
CloseApproach.__str__: uses time_str, neo.fullname, distance, velocity.
extract.py
load_neos: csv.DictReader (stdlib) reads column names automatically from the CSV header; passes named kwargs to NearEarthObject.
load_approaches: json.load (stdlib) reads the file; zip(fields, row) converts each data row into a dict keyed by the fields array from the JSON.
database.py
__init__: builds _by_designation and _by_name dicts (standard Python dict comprehensions) for O(1) lookup, then loops once over approaches to set approach.neo and append to neo.approaches.
get_neo_by_designation / get_neo_by_name: one-liner dict.get() calls.
query: adds if all(f(approach) for f in filters) guard — AttributeFilter.__call__ is the predicate.
filters.py
5 subclasses (DateFilter, DistanceFilter, VelocityFilter, DiameterFilter, HazardousFilter): each overrides get to extract the right attribute. DateFilter.get calls approach.time.date() so it compares date objects correctly.
create_filters: builds a list, appending only the filters whose argument is not None. Uses operator.eq/ge/le (stdlib operator module).
limit: uses itertools.islice (stdlib) — returns the original iterator if n is falsy, otherwise wraps it.
write.py
write_to_csv: csv.DictWriter (stdlib) with the already-defined fieldnames tuple. potentially_hazardous is written as a string ('True'/'False').
write_to_json: builds a list of dicts with a nested 'neo' dict, then calls json.dump (stdlib). diameter_km stays as a Python float so JSON encodes it correctly; potentially_hazardous stays as a Python bool.
